summary: another thing that makes a spider-man story is that being spider-man sucks. it really, really sucks. peter parker gets almost...
body:
another thing that makes a spider-man story is that being spider-man sucks. it really, really sucks. peter parker gets almost killed at every altercation, he helps police apprehend crime bosses but the police are predisposed against him (he’s a vigilante, so naturally that will be the case) so even if he helps he’s at the risk of getting arrested, the villains he faces get stronger and stronger but he remains as he is, and alone more often than not when stopping them, j jonah jameson yells at him and convinces the masses to do so as well, and being spider-man messes with his personal relationships, his job, maintaining his apartment, taking care of himself, etc

it is a thankless job, and oftentimes, he doesn’t get thanks. but writers give him a little bit of light in his shitty life. maybe a kid will thank him for getting back their cat; maybe he gets a sarcastic comment from an old lady who he saved from getting hit by the bus (he knows she’s thankful). maybe aunt may sends him a message that she’s been thinking of him recently. maybe mj tells him he did good work.

then peter is reminded why this is worth it, and why he must keep pushing on. give him a little act of kindness and he’ll give a world of kindness back. give him no act of kindness and he’ll still show kindness, because maybe you’ll learn by example? he’ll always think of how some people never had the kindness he received in his life, and that he must impart some to the world. and even if you don’t learn by example, his heart will still rest easier knowing he was as kind as he could be.

summary: He'd been awake for seven months when Loki turned up again, this time perched on the back of one of his couches.  "You could...
body:
He’d been awake for seven months when Loki turned up again, this time perched on the back of one of his couches.

“You could have knocked,” Steve said, after jumping.

“I could have,” Loki agreed. “Where is it you vanish to?” He still had that more curious than concerned tone of voice.

“What do you mean,” Steve said flatly, playing dumb. Loki frowned.

“Do not think I have failed to observe that you disappear for periods of time now and then, only to reappear, apparently without cause.”

“Why does it matter to you?” Steve asked, perhaps a little rudely.

“I am curious.”

Steve felt a sudden urge to tell him, without knowing why. Maybe because Loki probably wouldn’t look at him with pity. Would probably just shrug and leave again without caring at all. He held it back, though. “Well, I guess you’ll have to stay curious.”

From I’m Only Sleeping, by Lise
